    <segment id="1" parent="8" relname="preparation">
I agree with the comments about ease of use.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="8" relname="span">  Ease of use refers to the
property of a product or thing that a user can operate without having to
overcome a steep learning curve.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration"> Things with high ease of use will be
intuitive to the average user in the target market for the product.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="2" relname="elaboration"> The
term is often used as a goal during the design of a product, as well as
being used for marketing purposes.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="10" relname="span"> Put simply, things with &quot;high ease of
use&quot; are easy to use.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="9" relname="span">
However, some experts distinguish ease of use from ease of learning,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="circumstance">
especially when the design of a product involves a tradeoff between the
two goals.</segment>
